post_text:
Meal Payments

For convenience & safety, we encourage pre-payment of meals and snacks. Payment options are as follows:

Create an on-line account with MySchoolBucks.com to have accessibility to your student’s account and be able to deposit money on-line.

Checks can be made out to: Northwestern Regional School Food Service and brought directly to the cashier to be deposited in your child’s account. Cash is discouraged this year due to COVID-19.

If you have questions related to this system please contact Becky Tyrrell, Food Services Director, at tyrrell@edadvance.org or 860-567-0863.

post_text:
Congratulations to Beth Christensen (Class of 2020)! Beth was one of the three high school students awarded a scholarship from the United Nations Association of Connecticut, facilitated through the Northwest Connecticut Community Foundation and the Hartford Foundation for Public Giving.
These scholarships, available to any high school student in CT, aim to encourage and support students with a demonstrated interest in promoting world peace through work in international relations and diplomatic service and to cultivate an understanding of, and support for, the work of the UN in the United States. Congratulations!

post_text: Mr. Gary Franklin has been announced as the new Principal at Northwestern Regional High School! Mr. Franklin has served as the House 2 Assistant Principal for the past four years. He was also a Social Studies teacher and Department Chair, as well as a Dean of Students, at Newtown High School from 2012-2016. post_text:
Attention Parents and Staff Members:

You may know that the Commissioner has asked each of the six Regional Education Service Centers to create a Regional Advisory Team to gather and analyze feedback from stakeholders related to reopening schools. Our Superintendent, Dr. Palmer, has been named to the EdAdvance Committee. We are entering the first phase of this important work. An online tool called ThoughtExchange will be used to garner feedback from parents and staff members across the state. This tool is entirely confidential and users remain anonymous. Your participation will be essential in informing our state leaders as decisions are made regarding the reopening of our schools. Parents and staff members (ONLY), please use the following link to share your thoughts and help evaluate the critical issues we are facing.

Thought Exchange Link: https://my.thoughtexchange.com/493894984

post_text: The Highlander Basketball Camp will return for its 29th consecutive year running from July 13 to July 17, 2020. The basketball camp provides instruction, drills, and games for all boys and girls entering grades 3-8. The camp offers an opportunity for young boys and girls from each town to work together and build relationships before entering the middle and high school. The camp also provides an opportunity for young people to safely exercise, socialize, and learn about teamwork and sportsmanship along with the skills and knowledge to become better basketball players. Although these are uncertain times, the camp is still receiving sign ups daily and we will be proceeding as normal with our registration period. If we need to cancel camp a full refund will be sent back to parents and guardians. For more information and registration forms please visit our website at highlandercamp.webs.com

post_text:
Help us Celebrate Northwestern’s Healthcare Heroes!

As you read from Dr. Palmer’s message yesterday we are working on a video project to honor the healthcare heroes in the Northwestern community. Dr. Palmer wrote:

The news is full of stories of extraordinary healthcare professionals who are selflessly providing care for those who are sick with COVID-19. As we know, healthcare workers are experiencing many trials and tribulations. We admire their inner strength and are grateful for their work. Their determination to be brave, unselfish and caring is inspiring. Together they are a force of love.
We know that many of these caring professionals are part of our NWR7 school community. We feel it is a great time to honor those who are connected to our schools by creating a “Northwestern’s Healthcare Heroes” video.

We need your help! Please send a picture of your Northwestern Healthcare Hero to gfranklin@nwr7.org. In the message, please identify who the picture is of, their connection to Northwestern, if an alumni, the year they graduated and where they are working to fight COVID-19.

post_text:
To spread some positivity and lift each other up during our time apart, we will be hosting our very own NWR7 Virtual Spirit Week from Monday, April 6th through Thursday, April 9th!

Here is the list of themes for each day:

Monday, April 6th - Pajama Day - Share a pic of you in your coziest jammies!

Tuesday, April 7th - Together Tuesday - Take a selfie with a family member or pet!

Wednesday, April 8th - Work Hard Wednesday - Snap a pic of you distance learning!

Thursday, April 9th - Highlander Day - Rep our school by rocking some NWR7 apparel!

Each day you can share your virtual spirit week pictures by emailing them to me at sbrody@nwr7.org or by tagging us on social media using the hashtag #NWR7VirtualSpiritWeek.

We will share your pictures on our school’s social media to show that no matter the circumstances, we will always be proud to be Highlanders!

post_text:
Jane Doe No More and the professional team at East Coast Training Systems is proud to announce that a FREE self-defense training classes for women and girls ages 12 and over is being hosted by Northwestern. This self-defense class is being held on March 14th in our gym from 9:00 a.m. -1:00 p.m. Participants will learn awareness and prevention tips, escape strategies, and striking techniques designed to disable assailants and enable escape.

There are no pre-requisites for our classes: Escape Alive participants work at their own pace to learn skills and techniques that will work for them, regardless of age, strength, size or prior training.

For more information, email info@janedoenomore.org

If you are interested, please register here: https://www.janedoenomore.org/registration/index?event=5e419c72b176a2626b33c52b

post_text: Northwestern will be hosting a screening of the film Uprooting Addiction: Healing from the Ground Up, followed by a panel discussion and question and answer session that will be facilitated by clinicians from Greenwoods referral services and some of the subjects in the film in our auditorium. The producers of the film will also be present. The presentation is designed for parents of high school students and their children to attend together. Parents and students from The Gilbert School are also invited to participate in this event. Please make every effort to attend this important forum.

Order your 2019-2020 Northwestern Regional Middle School Yearbook today!

Pricing:

Early Bird Special: January 13th - January 31st: $18.00 per book

Regular Price: February 1st – April 1st: $20.00 per book

All orders must be placed no later than Wednesday, April 1st, 2020.

How to Order:

Fill out the yearbook order form. Order forms and payments should be filled out and turned in to the Middle School Office. Please make all checks payable to RSD7 in blue or black ink. Be sure to provide the correct amount per the deadlines listed above. Extra order forms are available in the Middle School Office, or you can download and print the attached form.

ONLINE ORDERING AVAILABLE:
You can order online by going to: http://jostensyearbooks.com/?REF=A01106167

*Online orders must be placed by the deadlines specified above.

If you have any questions, please contact Ms. Stephanie Brody at sbrody@nwr7.org.

On Saturday evening, February 8, 2020 the Civil Rights Stories students are hosting a wonderful one act play about one of the greatest champions of Civil and Human Rights in our country's history, Frederick Douglass. The play is called Free to Be and will be performed for parents, community members and middle school / high school students at 7 pm. Tickets are just $10 and can be purchased from any Civil Rights student, Mr. Stapleton or on-line at the following link.

http://bit.ly/CRS-NWR7

Gordon College Athletics
December 3, 2019 at 3:01 PM ·

Ben North is Gordon's Athlete of the Week! The sophomore netted a career-high 13 points in a non-conference victory over Salem State last week. North also brought down six rebounds, grabbed three steals, and had a pair of blocks. Congrats Ben!
